{
  "doc_id": "3677",
  "text": "CD44s is a favorable prognostic factor in neuroblastoma [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and the epigenetic inactivation of CD44 expression through methylation has been reported as a potential culprit in the process of neuroblastoma development [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In the xenograft model, inhibitors of DNA methylation as well as induction of CD44 expression suppress neuroblastoma growth [CITATION_5] . Clinical studies have associated CD44 expression with low-stage differentiated neuroblastoma while high-risk aggressive tumors lack expression of this antigen [CITATION_6] . In this study, we have demonstrated that CD44s can be used as a marker to isolate neuroblastoma cells capable of subcutaneous xenograft formation and organ infiltration in NOD/SCID animals; in addition we provide evidence that these tumors remained negative for CD44.",
